<br>
I could have picked a better example for the drinking husband. To restate the point I was attemping to make is that if one spouse was doing something the other felt was in  excess and the two of them couldn't work that issue with the behavoir out with some sort of compromise, then they are to blame not the activity.<br>
<br>
To respond to your last paragraph, I agree 48 hours isn't the place to go for news. But I do still feel that in general a trend towards that type of journalism instead of focusing on facts prevails. The media directly caused a change in pattern of the targets to be picked in the sniper incident for instance. The media influences wars, who you pick for politcal officer etc. <br>
<br>
I feel that the news media as such has a responsibility to report facts first, and to make clear when they venture into the area of opinion. Instead they are reporting and stating criminals who are not yet tried as guilty by their labeling. The woman who was on video tape hitting her child was tried in the media long before it was handled by the authorities. <br>
<br>
I guess using alleged or suspected is too much to ask these days though... it appears to be far easier just to sue for damages later on. <br>
<br>
edit - got this from the 48 hours site - a description of what their program is supposed to be. I figured it might spark some discussion in relation to this thread. <br>
&quot;<br>
(CBS) When 48 Hours premiered in 1988, Time magazine said it could be the most innovative prime-time news series since 60 Minutes debuted in 1968. In its unique approach, 48 Hours delves into a single subject, examining it from multiple angles with its saturation coverage and action-driven style. 48 Hours Investigates is now in its 16th season. The broadcast has received critical acclaim reflected in almost 20 Emmy awards, a George Foster Peabody Award, and an Ohio State Award. <br>
<br>
48 Hours Investigates airs Fridays at 8 p.m. ET/PT. Check local listings. &quot;<br>
